1 Background Information

These data within the USFWS and USGS dataset was collected primarily during experimental harvests primarily conducted in the 1960s and 1970s, or during sea otter captures related to USFWS and USGS sea otter sampling and tagging studies conducted from the late 1980s up to and including 2019, or recovered dead during the 1989 Exxon Valdez Oil spill (EVOS).

We were interested to see if there were any differences between the otters that were captured before and after the oil spill.

First, well want to create a new variable called oil_spill where the dataset will be split into before_oil_spill and after_oil_spill. This variable will also be factored so that the years will be in chronological order.

#sea otters after the oil spill
seot <- seot %>% 
  mutate(oil_spill = case_when(YEAR < 1989 ~ "before_oil_spill", 
                               YEAR > 1989 ~ "after_oil_spill"))

seot$oil_spill <- factor(seot$oil_spill, levels = c("before_oil_spill", "after_oil_spill"))

The two-way ANOVA suggests that there is a statistical significance with the interaction between the two variables FINAL_AGE and oil_spill for the dependent variable WEIGHT, we will have to perform any analysis of simple events. 3.0.4.3 Statistical Analysis

We are performing a statistical analysis on the body length of adult otters before and after the Exxon Oil Spill. This is an analysis of two variables (one qualitative, one quantitative), where there are two groups being compared against parametric, independent samples. This suggests that we should use a Welch Two Sample t-test for statistical analysis.

#Welch's Two Sample t-test
t_test_length <- t.test(true_standard_lgth ~ oil_spill, data = seot_west_aleutians)
t_test_length
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  true_standard_lgth by oil_spill
## t = 1.0462, df = 350.38, p-value = 0.2962
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group before_oil_spill and group after_oil_spill is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.8228886  2.6933877
## sample estimates:
## mean in group before_oil_spill  mean in group after_oil_spill 
##                       121.0256                       120.0904

REPORT: There was no significant impact of the oil spill on the body length of the sea otter population (Welch Two Sample t-test; t = -1.0462, df = 350.38, p-value = 0.2962).

3.0.5.3 Statistical Analysis

We are performing a statistical analysis on the body length of adult otters before and after the Exxon Oil Spill. This is an analysis of two variables (one qualitative, one quantitative), where there are two groups being compared against parametric, independent samples. This suggests that we should use a Welch Two Sample t-test for statistical analysis.

#Welch's Two Sample t-test
t_test_length <- t.test(BACULA_LGTH ~ oil_spill, data = seot_west_aleutians)
t_test_length
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  BACULA_LGTH by oil_spill
## t = -4.6688, df = 183.77, p-value = 5.829e-06
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group before_oil_spill and group after_oil_spill is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -2.605329 -1.057485
## sample estimates:
## mean in group before_oil_spill  mean in group after_oil_spill 
##                       14.01716                       15.84857
#two-way ANOVA
two_anova_lgth_bac <- aov(BACULA_LGTH ~ oil_spill + FINAL_AGE + oil_spill:FINAL_AGE, data = seot_west_aleutians)
summary(two_anova_lgth_bac)
##                      Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
## oil_spill             1  200.1   200.1   60.99 1.19e-12 ***
## FINAL_AGE             1  995.8   995.8  303.45  < 2e-16 ***
## oil_spill:FINAL_AGE   1   74.7    74.7   22.78 4.50e-06 ***
## Residuals           141  462.7     3.3                     
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 2869 observations deleted due to missingness

With there being no statistical significance with the interaction between the two variables FINAL_AGE and oil_spill for the dependent variable BACULA_LGTH, we dont have to perform any analysis of simple events.

REPORT: There was a significant difference in baculum sizes in adult male otters before and after the Exxon Mobil oil spill in 1989 (Welch Two Sample t-test; t = 4.6688, df = 183.77, p-value = 0.005). The average baculum length for adult male otters before the oil spill was 14.02 mm and 15.85 mm after the oil spill.

There was no significant impact of the oil spill on the body length of the sea otter population (Two-way ANOVA; F_1,3375, f = 0.207, p=0.65). There was a significant impact on the age of the otter on the body length (Two-way ANOVA; F_1,3375, f = 2297.583, p < 0.0005).

3.0.7.3 Statistical Analysis

We are performing a statistical analysis on the ages of captured adult otters before and after the Exxon Oil Spill. This is an analysis of two variables (one qualitative, one quantitative), where there are two groups being compared against parametric, independent samples. This suggests that we should use a Welch Two Sample t-test for statistical analysis.

#Welch's t-test
t.test(data = seot, FINAL_AGE ~ oil_spill)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  FINAL_AGE by oil_spill
## t = 12.825, df = 3472.6, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group before_oil_spill and group after_oil_spill is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.566355 2.131725
## sample estimates:
## mean in group before_oil_spill  mean in group after_oil_spill 
##                       6.619682                       4.770642

REPORT: The otters captured before the oil spill were significantly older than the otters captured after the oil spill (Welch Two Sample t-test; t = -12.825, df = 3472.6, p-value < 0.005).
